[
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "what are derivatives?"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "A derivative of a function at any given point is its instantaneous rate of change at that point. You can also think of the derivative of a function as the graph of the slopes of that function."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "notations"
  },
  {
    "type": "ol",
    "contents": [
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "prime notation: $ f'(x) $ (or $ y' $) is the derivative of $ f(x) $ (or $ y $)."
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "delta notation: $ \\frac {d} {dx} f(x) $ (or $ \\frac {dy} {dx} $) is the derivative of $ f(x) $ (or $ y $)."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "visualization"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The following video demonstrates how the derivative of a function is determined, by first calculating the slope at a given point and then plotting it onto the graph:"
  },
  {
    "type": "video",
    "url": "/lectures/videos/determine-derivative-1.mp4",
    "content": "The blue graph is the derivative of $ f(x) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Note that the straight line on the $ f(x) $ curve is the **tangent** of that curve."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Also, notice that when the value of the derivative gets closer to zero, the tangent becomes more flat. This makes sense, since the deriviative of a function is the value of the slope at a particular point."
  },
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "Determining the derivative of a function"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "As of now, we can only find the derivative of a function at a given point, but what if we want the actual function that represents the derivative of a function?"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "We can do this by using the formula for the instantaneous rate of change at a point, but instead of treating $a$ as a point, we use $x$ instead:"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Derivative by first principle"
  },
  {
    "type": "latex",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {dy} {dx} = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {f(x + h) - f(x)} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "example"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Determine the derivative of the following function: $ f(x) = x^2 + x $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Using the first principle method, we can calculate the derivative:"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {f(x + h) - f(x)} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac { [(x + h)^2 + (x + h)] - [x^2 + x]} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac { x^2 + 2hx + h^2 + x + h - x^2 - x} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac { \\cancel{x^2} + 2hx + h^2 \\cancel{ + x} + h \\cancel{ - x^2} \\cancel{ - x}} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac { 2hx + h^2 + h } {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac { h (2x + h + 1) } {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac { \\cancel{h} (2x + h + 1) } {\\cancel{h}} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} (2x + h + 1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = 2x + (0) + 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = 2x + 1 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore f'(x) = 2x + 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "Practice Questions"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 1"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "For the function $ f(x) = \\frac {x} {2x - 1} $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "a) Determine its derivative $ f'(x) $."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "b) Determine the equation of the tangent line to $ f(x) $ at $ x = 1 $."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "a) To find the derivative, we will use the first principles formula:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {f(x + h) - f(x)} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {\\frac {x + h} {2(x + h) - 1} - \\frac {x} {2x - 1}} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {\\frac {x + h} {2x + 2h - 1} - \\frac {x} {2x - 1}} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {\\frac {(x + h)(2x - 1)} {(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} - \\frac {x(2x + 2h - 1)} {(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)}} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {(x + h)(2x - 1) - x(2x + 2h - 1)} {h(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {2x^2 - x + 2hx - h - 2x^2 - 2xh + x} {h(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {\\cancel{2x^2} \\cancel{-x} \\cancel{+2hx} - h \\cancel{-2x^2} \\cancel{-2xh} + \\cancel{x}} {h(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {-h} {h(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {-\\cancel{h}} { \\cancel{h} (2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {-1} {(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {-1} {(2x - 1)(2x + 2(0) - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {-1} {(2x - 1)(2x - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {-1} {(2x - 1)^2} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "b) To find the tangent equation at for $ f(x) $ at $ x = 1 $, we need $ f(1) $ and $ f'(1) $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(1) = \\frac {1} {2(1) - 1} = \\frac {1} {2 - 1} = 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(1) = \\frac {-1} {(2(1) - 1)^2} = \\frac {1} {1^2} = 1 = m_T $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now, we just need to plug in the values into the following equation of a tangent line:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y - y_1 = m_T(x - x_1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y - (1) = (1)(x - (1)) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y = (x - 1) + 1 $"
  }
]
